# Visual Explainer Document — Skill & Schema

## Purpose

Create a single-page interactive website that explains how a codebase works. The document must be self-contained (HTML + embedded CSS + embedded JS), visually rich, and keep pace with the source code via automated staleness checks.

---

## Required Sections (follow this order)

Every explainer document MUST include these sections. Each section maps to a `<section id="...">` element.

### 1. Hero

- Gradient headline with project name
- One-sentence description of what the project does
- **Stats bar**: file count, lines of code, test count, feature count
- These stats must be derived from the actual codebase at generation time

### 2. Architecture Overview

- **Card grid** (one card per isolated component/context)
  - Card title = component name
  - Card subtitle = filename(s) + line count
  - Bullet list of responsibilities
  - Top-border color to visually distinguish components
- **Data flow diagram**: use inline `<div class="flow">` with nodes and arrows showing how data moves between components
- **Key config snippet**: syntax-highlighted code block of the project's entry-point config (e.g., `manifest.json`, `package.json`)

### 3. Core Algorithm(s)

- Visual representation of the algorithm's input structure (e.g., a DOM tree, a data pipeline, a request flow)
- Use a styled `<div>` with monospace font, color-coded node types, and arrow annotations
- Syntax-highlighted code block of the core function, with `<span class="hl">` highlight on the key lines
- Explain the **branching logic** (what gets processed vs. skipped and why)

### 4. Pattern Matching / Filtering Logic

- **Interactive demo**: input fields where the user can type values, a button to run the logic, and a result `<div>` that updates live
- **Pre-built example grid**: 2-column grid showing 4+ patterns with expected results (MATCH / NO MATCH, color-coded)
- Code block showing the matching function

### 5. Input Processing / Transformation

- **Interactive demo**: input text + parameters + action button → result with visual diff (strikethrough for removed, highlight for added)
- Code block showing the transformation logic, highlighting the key branching decision
- Explain edge cases that were discovered during development

### 6. Performance Optimizations

- **Flow diagram** showing the optimization pipeline (e.g., Event → Debounce → Single Execution)
- Code block (keep it short — the "6 lines that cut CPU by 90%" pattern)
- Link to any standalone deep-dive explainer if one exists

### 7. Inter-Component Communication

- **Timeline** using a vertical line with colored dots for each step
- Each step: title (what happens) + description (which API/function is called)
- Color-code by component (use the same colors as the Architecture cards)

### 8. Data Persistence / Storage

- Code block showing the storage abstraction
- **Data shape example**: a styled JSON block showing the exact structure stored
- Note any cross-platform quirks (e.g., sync vs. local fallback)

### 9. Data Import / Export

- **Card grid** (one card per supported format)
  - Format name, file signature (how to detect it)
  - Field mapping bullets
- If there's CSV, note quoting/escaping rules

### 10. Bugs & Lessons Learned

- **Bug cards**: each with a red header (bug title), description, and a green header (fix title) with the corrected code
- Focus on bugs that are **non-obvious** — regex pitfalls, timing issues, boundary failures
- Include before/after code diffs inside the card

### 11. Feature Map

- **Full-width table** with columns: Feature | Category | File(s) | Key Pattern
- Category uses colored badge pills: Core, Perf, UX, Data (or project-relevant categories)
- Every user-facing feature AND every internal optimization must appear here

